The function
\[f(z) = \frac{(-1 + i \sqrt{3}) z + (-2 \sqrt{3} - 18i)}{2}\]represents a rotation around some complex number $c$.  Find $c$.
inference:
Let $f(z) = \frac{(-1 + i \sqrt{3}) z + (-2 \sqrt{3} - 18i)}{2}$.
Let $c$ be the center of rotation. Then $f(c) = c$.
$\frac{(-1 + i \sqrt{3}) c + (-2 \sqrt{3} - 18i)}{2} = c$.
$(-1 + i \sqrt{3}) c + (-2 \sqrt{3} - 18i) = 2c$.
$(-1 + i \sqrt{3}) c - 2c = 2 \sqrt{3} + 18i$.
$c(-1 + i \sqrt{3} - 2) = 2 \sqrt{3} + 18i$.
$c(-3 + i \sqrt{3}) = 2 \sqrt{3} + 18i$.
$c = \frac{2 \sqrt{3} + 18i}{-3 + i \sqrt{3}}$.
$c = \frac{2 \sqrt{3} + 18i}{-3 + i \sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{-3 - i \sqrt{3}}{-3 - i \sqrt{3}} = \frac{(-2 \sqrt{3} - 18i)(-3 - i \sqrt{3})}{(-3)^2 + (\sqrt{3})^2} = \frac{(2 \sqrt{3})(-3 - i \sqrt{3}) + 18i(-3 - i \sqrt{3})}{9 + 3} = \frac{-6 \sqrt{3} - 6i \sqrt{3} - 54i - 18i^2 \sqrt{3}}{12} = \frac{-6 \sqrt{3} - 6i \sqrt{3} - 54i + 18 \sqrt{3}}{12} = \frac{12 \sqrt{3} - 6i \sqrt{3} - 54i}{12} = \sqrt{3} - \frac{1}{2}i\sqrt{3} - \frac{9}{2}i = \sqrt{3} - \frac{9}{2} i - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i$.
$c = \sqrt{3} - \frac{9}{2} i - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i = \sqrt{3} - \frac{9}{2} i - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} i = \sqrt{3} - \left( \frac{9}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \right) i$.
$c = \sqrt{3} - \frac{9 + \sqrt{3}}{2} i$.

Final Answer: $\boxed{\sqrt{3} - \frac{9 + \sqrt{3}}{2} i}$
ground_truth:
Since a rotation around $c$ fixes $c$, the complex number $c$ must satisfy $f(c) = c$.  In other words,
\[c = \frac{(-1 + i \sqrt{3}) c + (-2 \sqrt{3} - 18i)}{2}\]Then $2c = (-1 + i \sqrt{3}) c + (-2 \sqrt{3} - 18i)$, so
\[(3 - i \sqrt{3}) c = -2 \sqrt{3} - 18i.\]Then
\begin{align*}
c &= \frac{-2 \sqrt{3} - 18i}{3 - i \sqrt{3}} \\
&= \frac{(-2 \sqrt{3} - 18i)(3 + i \sqrt{3})}{(3 - i \sqrt{3})(3 + i \sqrt{3})} \\
&= \frac{-6 \sqrt{3} - 6i - 54i + 18 \sqrt{3}}{12} \\
&= \frac{12 \sqrt{3} - 60i}{12} \\
&= \boxed{\sqrt{3} - 5i}.
\end{align*}
